post_text:
Parents As Teachers
Let's All Dance Together Apart!

Studio 23 in Hillsboro has prepared a video for families and littles to move together. As Parents as Teachers, we will use this as one of our group connections, even though we can't actually be together.
The video is just over 20 minutes long, and doesn't require special clothes or shoes. It would be helpful for one song to have a scarf or piece of fabric, or even a tissue to wave as you move.
To participate, please let me know if you are interested. You will then receive a link to the video and a download of motor skills you can expect at different ages of your children. The link will be available during August. Your request for the video will be counted as attendance for our records.

Susie Kliewer
Coordinator/Parent Educator
Marion County Parents as Teachers
Hillsboro, KS 67063
620-947-4041

post_text:
In the interests of social distancing and keeping contact with others to small groups, new student enrollment can be done by calling 785-983-4321 for an appointment to come in. Paperwork will be taken care of and we will email or call you with your Skyward login information once your information is entered into Skyward. You can then finish your enrollment process online in the comfort of your own home and at your convenience.

If you don't have internet or need help with your Skyward enrollment, please call for an appointment to come in.

Families of Pre-K students can get their enrollment paperwork taken care of when they come in to do the ASQ screening before school begins. This will be by appointment and more information regarding this will be coming soon.

Centre High School Graduation: Date: 7-4-2020 Time: 7:30 pm Location: Bud Peterson Field, @ Centre High School Parking: Graduates are asked to park in the parking lot in front of the school, and guests for the event are to park in the parking lot or on the west side of the football field.
Important Information: The graduating class of 2020 invites you to their graduation ceremony this Saturday evening. This event is a special time for our seniors and for Centre School. Patrons/guests attending the event will need to bring their own chairs and sit on the west side of the stadium. Each graduate will have a designated seating area for his/her guests. Please sit in the area reserved for the graduate you are celebrating. Practice social distancing and keep a distance of 6 feet between yourself and others that don't live in your immediate household. We also ask that everyone wear a mask while in attendance.

Thank You,
Donald Raymer Centre Schools

UPDATE: KDOT just called and the intersection will close on MONDAY.

Just talked with KDOT and they are looking at Friday to get things going on Hwy 77, depending on weather. BUT, the county has NOT ROCKED Xavier yet. Xavier may not get rocked until next week. So, if things do not dry out until then, they are telling us we will have to come in from the north: East on 340th towards Burdick (paved road) to 3100. South on 3100 to 310th. West on 310th to the school. We will not have a rocked access to the school from the south on Friday and probably into next week.

The school intersection at HWY 77 will be closed! There will be one lane traffic on HWY 77, but you will not be able to turn off at the school intersection. Please use the above detour.

Update: The school intersection of 310th & Hwy 77 will be closing next week sometime between May 27 and May 29, depending upon the weather. To get to school you will have to come from the east on 310th.

Note Directions to get to the school:

From the South: If coming from the south on Hwy 77, take 290th (east out of Lincolnville) or 300th east to Xavier. Turn north on Xavier to 310th. Turn back west on 310th until you get to the school. The county is to rock Xavier to make it an accessible road when it rains.

From the North: From Hwy 77 turn east on 340th, Lost Springs/Burdick road, go east, towards Burdick, 2 miles to 3100 Road. Turn south on 3100 and go south 3 miles to 310th. Turn back west on 310th until you get to the school. This road should be rocked.

post_text:
Parenting Hotline
KCSL’s Parent Helpline (1-800-CHILDREN) is designed to meet the needs of parents and caregivers who feel isolated and frustrated when trying to meet the challenges of raising children. Information, referrals and support are provided statewide anonymously to parents, relatives, caregivers, youth and professionals 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.

The Parent Helpline is also available as a mobile phone App. This is a free download that can be found by searching The Parent Helpline in either the Android or Apple stores. The App also contains links for Parent Tip Cards on the KCSL website or has simple one touch dialing if you decide you need additional information.

Top reasons for calls to the Parent Helpline include basic parenting, child development, behavior management, questions about reporting child abuse and neglect, mental health, legal concerns and information about programs/services. Call the Parent Helpline at either 1-800-CHILDREN or 1-800-332-6378 for resources, referrals and other information.

Good afternoon,

Attorneys Teresa Woody, Kansas Appleseed, and Casey Johnson, Kansas Legal Services, will be hosting two 'Know Your Rights' online events next week explaining Governor Kelly's executive order on evictions and foreclosures during COVID-19. We'll briefly discuss the executive order and suspension of court proceedings and then we'll take your questions LIVE during both events.

We're offering two opportunities for folks to tune in and get their questions answered. See below for event details.

Tuesday, April 7, 2 p.m.
Watch live on Kansas Appleseed's Facebook page: bit.ly/KAwebinar
OR participate on Zoom: https://zoom.us/j/471929521

Thursday, April 9, 12:30 p.m.
Watch live on Kansas Appleseed's Facebook page: bit.ly/KAwebinar
OR Participate on Zoom: https://zoom.us/j/804237445

Please share this information widely!

Summary of the executive order: bit.ly/eo2010explained



Thank you,

Joey

post_text:
Positive and Productive Childcare While the Kids Are Not in School
As parents, there are times our children drive us crazy! In this time of rapid change and, for most of us, some confinement at home, this can be especially true. Getting through the day can become tense, and we can be unsure about how to discipline our children.

Join Randy Sprick, a parent, a grandparent, and a world leader in effective behavior management, as he shares 10-Tips to help kids learn to become more independent and responsible. You will learn that you are already doing many things, exactly right and add strategies for making things better!

Please share this information with caregivers in your community.
April 8, 2 pm ET (1 pm CT, 12 pm MT, 11 am PT)
April 8, 8 pm ET (7 pm CT, 6 pm MT, 5 pm PT)
